The monastery of Birr, so called from the stream on which it stood. grew in after times into a town bearing the same name, for which Parsonstown is a modern substitute. Birr is set down by Keating as a boundary of ancient Meath (vol. i. p. 128, ed. Haliday). It was formerly part of Eile O‘Carroll, in Mun- ster, but is now at the S. W. extremity of the King's County, in Leinster, “in ipso Hiberniae meditullio.'' (Ussher. Wks. vi. p. 523⁴)
